### 🛠️ What Was Implemented

1. **Next.js Windows Build Fix (`kill EPERM`)**
   - **Root Cause**: When executing `next build`, static generation workers are spawned via `jest-worker`. On Windows, the process cleanup triggers `ChildProcess.kill('SIGKILL')`, throwing a fatal `EPERM` error because processes are either already terminating or locked. This escapes standard promise boundaries and crashes the CLI.
   - **Resolution**: I added a monkeypatch at the top of [apps/web/next.config.js](file:///D:/Work/Codex/Hackathon%20Projects/OpenAI%20Hackathon/.agent-worktrees/incident-m1-frontend/apps/web/next.config.js) that traps and ignores the `EPERM` error on `win32` platform builds. The production build now finishes successfully with exit code `0`.

2. **Dashboard Overview & Core Value Proposition**
   - **Dashboard**: Rewrote [page.tsx](file:///D:/Work/Codex/Hackathon%20Projects/OpenAI%20Hackathon/.agent-worktrees/incident-m1-frontend/apps/web/app/page.tsx) with a modern theme, a clear system-health overview, and a hero description displaying the value proposition.
   - **Golden State**: Added controls to view or reset the **Golden Demo Incident (`inc-demo-0001`)** which seeds the store and redirects directly to the war room.
   - **Manual Intake**: Built an intake modal with accessible fields, keyboard focus indicators, explicit `<label>` bindings, screen-reader announcements (`role="alert"`), and demo-simulated mode labels.
   - **Filter Persistence**: Selected filters (Service, Severity, Status) are persisted in `localStorage` and automatically loaded on mount.

3. **Incident Detail & War-Room Shell**
   - Created the war room interface at [apps/web/app/incidents/[id]/page.tsx](file:///D:/Work/Codex/Hackathon%20Projects/OpenAI%20Hackathon/.agent-worktrees/incident-m1-frontend/apps/web/app/incidents/%5Bid%5D/page.tsx):
     - **Header**: Visualizes severity, service, and workflow state with non-color icons + textual cues (e.g. `📥 RECEIVED`, `⚙️ NORMALIZING`).
     - **Chronological Timeline**: Lists historical steps taken during diagnosis.
     - **Evidence Provenance Panel**: Details kind, source, redaction, and has expandable raw JSON/log details.
     - **Hypotheses & Confidence**: Shows potential causes with interactive confidence progress meters, links to supporting evidence, and list of unknown variables.
     - **Remediation & Diff Patches**: Renders code diff views with green additions and red deletions, along with boundaries constraints and placeholders for earlier phases.
     - **Human Approval Forms**: Displays interactive buttons to **Approve & Execute Patch** or **Reject Patch** (calling the FastAPI backend) with required textual justification input.

4. **Expanded Tests & Types**
   - Added helper functions to [apps/web/lib/api.ts](file:///D:/Work/Codex/Hackathon%20Projects/OpenAI%20Hackathon/.agent-worktrees/incident-m1-frontend/apps/web/lib/api.ts) mapping backend sub-resources.
   - Expanded unit tests in [apps/web/lib/api.test.ts](file:///D:/Work/Codex/Hackathon%20Projects/OpenAI%20Hackathon/.agent-worktrees/incident-m1-frontend/apps/web/lib/api.test.ts) to verify endpoint parameters and HTTP error isolation.

5. **ADR and Handoff Documentation**
   - [docs/adr/frontend-m1-architecture.md](file:///D:/Work/Codex/Hackathon%20Projects/OpenAI%20Hackathon/.agent-worktrees/incident-m1-frontend/docs/adr/frontend-m1-architecture.md): Documented frontend architectural choices and EPERM build fix details.
